In my quest for an education in social work, I aim to follow a career path within the Division of Family and Children Services to aid children who have been abused or neglected, and to offer support to troubled families. The values I bring to the social work field consist of service, respect, ethical conduct, a commitment to enhancing relationships among others, and a dedication to my own professional growth to remain proficient in my field. These values are not merely important to social workers; they are central to who I am personally.

Throughout my years in high school and college, I witnessed many individuals turning away from their problems in denial or employing coping mechanisms that were suboptimal. It was these experiences that led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still undecided on a career path post-graduation from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a break. One summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained that he was escaping his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents’ residence. Seeking to help, I drove over and privately discussed my concerns with the police, sharing my recent degree in Psychology. The police asked me to talk to the parents, as they had reached a dead end legally. Despite the parents' nervousness and attempts to blame the son, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children navigate family disputes.

Another crucial value in social work is social justice. While society claims the individual's importance, the "individual" we mourn often adheres to outdated traditions rather than true uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why do we strive to be like everyone else? I embrace my individuality and resist placing limitations on myself. Throughout my high school and college years, I actively protested against social injustice: coloring my hair unnaturally, wearing unique clothing, piercing my ears beyond traditional standards, openly declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I stand for social justice and will continue to protest against injustice.

This paper delves into the Biological and Sociocultural models as they pertain to the sleep disorder insomnia. The Biological model centers on genetic factors and health aspects, while the Sociocultural model focuses on environmental influences and their relation to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. We'll explore each model and the research that supports them, examining their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized into primary, secondary, or substance-induced. Primary disorders include Dyssomnias (like insomnia) and Parasomnias (like sleepwalking), while secondary disorders are linked to mental health issues or substances. This review primarily focuses on insomnia and primary sleep disorders in the context of the Biological and Sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, heritable factors, and physiological aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study on mice found that GABAB receptors on orexin neurons control sleep/wake states. Activating the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, and inhibiting it reduces anxiety and induces sleep. Baclofen, a GABAB agonist, increased sleep time in mice, suggesting that the findings can be generalized to humans. This highlights a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans, with alterations potentially disrupting sleep without medication. Socioculturally, inheriting this phenotype could naturally regulate sleep, negatively impacting daily life tasks and focus.

This text explores three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a concise definition of the condition is provided. Secondly, the process of diagnosing CAPD is detailed, outlining common signs or "red flags". Lastly, the paper offers strategies for teachers in mainstream classrooms to assist students with CAPD.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is “the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Specifically, CAP refers to how the CNS perceives and processes auditory information, and the neural activity that supports this processing, resulting in electrophysiological auditory responses” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). It’s a disorder where the brain fails to properly interpret sounds, even though the individual hears normally. People with CAPD are not considered hearing impaired; instead, their brains struggle to distinguish words and filter out background noise.

The earliest reference to CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was termed “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari pioneered tests for children with communicative disorders in 1954, and in 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing, providing insights into the physiology behind CAPD. A national conference in 1977 sparked more research on children with the disorder.

CAPD presents in various ways: individuals may struggle to pinpoint sounds in space, differentiate between multiple sounds, recognize sound patterns, identify changes in speech, block out subsequent sounds, interpret sound clues, or follow the sequence of auditory information. Diagnosing CAPD involves systematic observation and auditory function tests, conducted by professionals like audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. These evaluations can include questionnaires, observations of auditory behaviors, and advanced tests that record and analyze responses within the ear. Currently, there is no single, conclusive diagnostic tool, and the cause of CAPD remains unknown.

The play Twelfth Night suggests that while disguise can be a handy tool for long-term deception, eventually a person must discard it or risk becoming trapped forever. Breaking the deception can lead to isolation, forcing one to choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships. While some may shrug off the deception, others could be offended. The issue of deception in gender role reversal is particularly tricky, as it raises questions like why someone would feel the need to adopt the guise of the opposite gender. Viola's case is a prime example: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Arriving in an unfamiliar land, Viola feels compelled to pretend to be a man to protect herself. Her plan succeeds but also isolates her from other women, excluding her from crucial support. Worse, she becomes so convincing as a man that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian, and falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) Additionally, Viola struggles with suppressed romantic feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261) Though this might seem progressive, to modern audiences, Twelfth Night could be seen as showcasing how deception can reveal hidden emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages hint that these characters may have unexpressed feelings that Viola/Cesario forces them to confront. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario as a man, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? It's likely not the latter, as Shakespeare's Olivia seems more interested in judging people by their appearances. This is evident in how easily Olivia shifts her affections from Cesario to Sebastian, seeing Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule was notorious for its harshness, particularly its role in the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in South West Africa. While it's impossible to encapsulate an entire colonial empire with such a simple description, the German colonial empire was as varied as its geography. Educational policies were just as diverse. When the British took over German East Africa in 1919, they found many educated and literate Africans. German efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were commended by contemporary authors. However, in South West Africa, the situation was starkly different. Unlike East Africa, where the government was heavily involved in native education, in South West Africa, mission societies primarily taught natives with limited government support. Meanwhile, the government invested heavily in the education of Europeans, setting up a state school system and supporting missionary schools. These policies had lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies had many literate and educated Africans, South West Africa saw the vast majority of its population remain uneducated and illiterate. Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience. This paper aims to explore these factors and delve into new research on settlers' and colonial authorities' attitudes toward native Africans.

There's a wide range of literature on education in the German colonial empire, with many sources in German from the early 20th century. These works primarily described the features of colonial educational systems. Later English writings expanded on this by comparing education across different colonies and providing more detailed analyses. These studies highlighted significant differences in educational systems. Cohen's work on education in South West Africa and East Africa is the most relevant to this topic. Cohen compares these colonies' educational systems and discusses factors explaining their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounts for many of the colony's educational system's distinctive features.

South West Africa had a moderate climate compared to other German colonies, with much of its territory covered in arid desert. Its European population reflected these hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived there, compared to East Africa's 5,336.

The classification of Popular Music has evolved over the past century, encompassing so many genres that it's difficult to list them all. Many genres, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have spawned numerous sub and sub-sub genres. Heavy Metal rock, in particular, has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in the past 40 years. It's expressive because of its wide range of emotions, leaning more towards the darker side. It's diverse due to the flexibility people discovered early on, leading to countless sub-genres and sub-sub-genres that continue today. Today, heavy metal has so many niches that it's hard to define what it is. It incorporates themes from other genres and has evolved from somewhere. To understand today's metal music, one must first understand the metal movement and why it's a movement, not just a genre.

A few decades before surrealists began painting dreamlike scenes, Henri Rousseau was crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. "The Dream," his 1910 masterpiece, is not just about a woman marveling at her dreamland, but also reflects Rousseau's personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. He longed for acceptance, praise, and recognition from artists and art lovers, wrestling with an internal struggle—either conforming to conventional styles to gain acceptance or staying true to his unique creativity. "The Dream" is his most poignant expression of this lifelong internal conflict: to imitate established styles or forge his own path.

To fully appreciate "The Dream," one must first know a bit about Rousseau's life. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, he was a tinsmith's son who never had formal art training. Instead, he worked as a gabelou for France until age forty and earned the nickname douanier, a customs inspector. After losing his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their infant children, he turned to painting for comfort. Unlike his peers, Rousseau was a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of the common people.

Rousseau's desire for art world acceptance is understandable given his background. He was untrained and older than many of his contemporaries, yet he produced works alongside well-known modern artists. Recognition for his art came around the time Matisse gained prominence. Jan Gordon, in "Modern French Painters," notes that Matisse and Rousseau were not just competitors but differed in style, subject matter, and motivations: "Matisse feared trite painting, while Rousseau yearned for a conventional picture to gain Artiste Français admission" (92).

Many a wise thinker has pondered the deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there's a fundamental reason for this symbiotic relationship. As John Keats put it in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty— That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While we often learn about ethics and aesthetics through education or life experiences, we seem to appreciate them intuitively, without explicit instruction. Both ethics and aesthetics are attempts to explain rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are primarily efforts to understand why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than rigid rules for judgment or creation.

Criticism of art or morals can never fully encapsulate the essence of what is good or beautiful. Discussions about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not define why it is considered good art. When asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people often say, "There's just something about it," followed by a more complex explanation. I believe that both art and morals possess an ineffable quality that cannot be fully described. As Flannery O'Connor put it, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Similarly, ethics has this same transcendent nature. As Wittgenstein noted, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that this elusive "something," this je ne sais quoi, is the most potent attribute of both ethics and aesthetics, and that their transcendental nature connects them.

I believe morality and art are closely linked because we experience their power most intensely at a noumenal level, using a Kantian term. They impact us in a way that can be experienced but not fully explained. This connection is particularly strong with the art of literature. As McKean observed, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Germany, as we know it today, is a united nation with a rich cultural tapestry stretching from the shadows of the Alps in München to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This unique blend of culture can be felt from Köln by the Rhine, through the heart of Germany, to the historic city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given this diversity, it's not surprising that Germany, as we know it, is a mosaic of various origins and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral homeland of the Germans, has an origin story shrouded in debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus suggested the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously called Germans before crossing the Rhine and clashing with Gaulish forces. Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, distinguishing between those he conquered (the Gauls) and those he did not. The origin of the name is uncertain, but it may come from the spear the Germans used in warfare, the "ger," or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating their loud nature.

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," described the Germans as aboriginal, not mixed with other races. He said, "Why would anyone leave Asia or Africa for Italy to settle in Germany with its harsh climate, wild lands, and gloomy demeanor?" (Tacitus, 98)

Meanwhile, the Romans were content to send out expeditions to Germany for goods and occasional land campaigns but ultimately returned to their vast empire. As Germanic tribes began appearing in the first century, they dwelt on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading their land-gotten goods and serving in the Roman army. (Ozment, 2005)

I stood there, eyes fixed on the scene before me, mind empty and blank, no emotions or thoughts intruding on the pure experience. I just observed, studied, letting my brain process the image in front of me with practiced ease. It was as if I wasn't thinking at all, just having a clear, fluid experience of what I was seeing. Once, I followed advice from an artist I worked with and bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain". I've always wanted to draw, and this book teaches everything from understanding a pencil to the brain's processes for interpreting lines. One of its techniques is to frame any picture you want to study with a square, turning an overwhelmingly detailed scene into something manageable.

Staring at the bowl of fruit in front of me, I couldn't mentally place that square frame. I was so captivated, so awestruck that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of my perspective being artistic, then this was the start of my picture, the beginning of my story, "Work in Brown".

Fingertips touched the brush, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's will given form in what could be the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, clear and calm, crystal clear and clean. Matter broke away, disappearing into nothingness. My hand smacked the brush on the toilet again, muscles tensing, jerking more quickly, more anxious the second time. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.

Mop in hand, feet set wide apart, tie knotted tightly around my neck, I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter. A few flushes later, and I was ready, hand reaching for the toilet paper, wrapping itself around my hand until it looked like an oven mitt. Standing up straight, bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey....

Teenagers are dropping like flies behind the wheel. Several factors combine to create this grim reality for America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that a big part of the problem is that teen brains aren't fully equipped to handle the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience is another key factor. This inexperience leads to more fatal accidents, vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens also have a harder time when they're on the road with their peers, which, admittedly, they usually are. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a clear correlation between the age of passengers and traffic accidents.
California and other states have tried to make teen driving safer by implementing provisional licenses that limit driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, these measures are just temporary fixes. The real issue is that as a group, the youngest drivers aren't ready to handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 might be too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reported that Zuckerman's research shows a strong desire among those under 19-20 to take risks for the thrill. Therefore, it makes sense to delay driving until this tendency to seek thrills has subsided. If we keep issuing driver's licenses to young teens, we'll continue to see deadly accidents and the death toll could reach alarming proportions in the next few years. By 2010, a new wave of teen drivers will be hitting the road.
Legislation addressing this issue wouldn't be too complicated. Schools could still offer driver's education, but no one under 18 could drive. Provisional permits could still be issued before a full license, and a certain number of practical driving hours would still be required, based on the majority of states' requirements (like California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours with an adult). Since teen driving deaths occur across all states, uniform, national legislation would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teens nationwide.
The proposed legislation is far from a new idea.

As I flipped through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to check out the fifteen trick films made between 1895 and 1901. These films typically leverage creative editing to create optical illusions. My analysis mainly focused on detailing the poetic elements of the majority of trick films and examining the unique characteristics present in a few of the latter ones. Generally, trick films during the turn of the century are confined to a set within a frontal proscenium, featuring no camera movement, and using long and medium shots, adhering to the rule of one shot equaling one film. However, some films at the start of the twentieth century dared to disrupt these conventions by incorporating elements like multiple shots.

One of the most striking similarities among these trick films is their filming within an interior set, confined within the boundaries of a frontal proscenium. The camera remains static in its position, not following figures or objects. This composition was prevalent in early films and drew inspiration from theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation of using a stage is that figures in trick films usually only move side-to-side, never walking towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis, with the camera not following them even when they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium style also means that shots are typically long and, less frequently, medium shots. Close-up shots are absent in all Edison catalog trick films. This stems from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience views the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. Actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, precluding close-ups.

Most early trick films adhere to the pattern that one conceptual shot equals one film. This restricts film length to about a minute or less, depending on frames per second. It also limits their dramatic or narrative use; they usually feature short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and switching feats with minimal story. However, in a trick film, a single conceptual shot for the viewer does not correspond to one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually consist of several joined together to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance. Carefully examine The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a notable early trick film. A closer look reveals that the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” starts even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, was a steadfast early advocate of Republicanism. Despite primarily being an agriculturalist, his career in politics shaped him into a vocal champion of personal liberties and governance. His deep-rooted dedication to an agrarian lifestyle permeated his views on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and the judicial system.

Taylor believed that America had the unique chance to establish an ideal system due to the absence of native traditions that could hinder its creation. He strongly championed the natural rights of man, emphasizing that they are interconnected and that denying any one of them weakens the value of the rest. He contended that these rights should be beyond government reach. He referred to what others called the "state of nature" as a system where physical prowess and malevolent intellect dominated, but he believed that in society, this dynamic needed to be different.

To cultivate this ideal society, Taylor envisioned a government that accounted for both the inherent good and evil within humanity. He was rigid in his dualistic morality, asserting that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). Good principles, he argued, were those that protected private property, enhanced agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. A government rooted in such principles, he believed, would function equitably regardless of its administrators, who he assumed would be driven by avarice and self-interest. He considered self-interest a fundamental human trait, but only detrimental when it led to the creation of sub-societies that exploited others. A strong government was necessary to manage this natural evil, he argued, but it must be closely monitored to prevent the introduction of malicious principles.

Taylor, like many of his Republican contemporaries, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He called for a highly restricted Federal government, with only the powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He understood that an extensive Federal government could be costly and potentially tyrannical. However, he warned against a simple, literal interpretation, arguing that it could easily become corrupt without considering the intentions of the Founding Fathers. He considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly describes the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Referring back to Figure 17, commuter log submissions took a steep dive in the third month of the project. This decline was a bit discouraging, and the reasons behind it are unclear. With the arrival of winter in a New England campus, fewer people commute by bicycle or on foot, which might explain part of the drop. December also sees the end of the fall semester, when students and faculty are busy wrapping up schoolwork and grades, potentially leading to the log submissions falling off their radar. The holiday season brings a month-long break for many, with no need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January, possibly accounting for the low log submissions in February. However, none of these factors explains the low February submissions. It's possible that any new project experiences an initial surge of enthusiasm, followed by a natural decrease. To combat this, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which boosted log submissions. Maintaining project momentum while dealing with the natural decline in engagement and semester breaks in higher education was a significant challenge. Another hurdle was the cultural preference for driving cars, so providing incentives for alternative commuting modes was crucial. We offered various prizes like gift cards to local businesses, but even larger prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars could have likely increased participation and engagement. If the prize value had increased over time, say announcing a bicycle in December, a hybrid or electric car in January, it might have kept participation and engagement high instead of declining. The prize offerings remained consistent throughout the project.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security that aims to replicate an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets similar to a traditional index fund, but it trades like a stock on an exchange. It offers the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership, such as the ability to sell short, purchase on margin, and buy as few as one share. Despite these advantages, ETFs charge a commission for trades, like stocks. Another appealing feature of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. However, it's essential for a prudent financial investor to assess the actual benefits, such as diversification, and their extent. For this exercise, we'll examine the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings to determine if owning a single ETF matches the benefits of a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and if there are better configurations of the same stocks for a higher Sharpe ratio or return.

To streamline our evaluation, we'll include only the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the ETF's assets. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To gauge how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return, using the current asset percentages and normalizing them to 100%. The results are presented in the chart below.

The chart shows that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF's overall Beta. These results suggest that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could offer a higher return with a lower Beta. However, it's important to note that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different.

To determine if these portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with the ETF IHF's.

Dream-land, a poem Edgar Allan Poe famously dubbed one of his finer works, utilizes the term "Thulé" in stanzas 6 and 56, a reference that scholar Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil employed this term to denote an island north of Britain, a boundary of known world for the Greeks. While Virgil's use is undeniable, there's a present-day source Poe might have drawn from, given his keen interest in German literature.

This connection highlights Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," notes the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe likely imitated the latter. Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned playwright of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second, the year of his death, 1832. Within Faust's second part lies a poem titled "The King of Thule," a tale about a king who, bereft of his wife after she gifts him a goblet, descends into drunkenness and despair, then resolves to die, bequeathing the goblet to his children before throwing it into the sea. This character's plight and the desolate landscape Poe describes in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, perhaps a dark reflection of Poe's own struggles with loss and alcohol.

Poe uses "Thule" twice in his writings, including the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." The term bookends "Dream-Land," making these two poems companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule as a dark, lonely place haunted by dead friends and devoid of color, mirroring the despair of Goethe's king. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be interpreted as a conversation between the two poets.

Goethe was a prominent author, and Poe, though not directly connected to him, likely knew of his work due to his admiration for Tennyson. Poe's respect for Tennyson and the numerous reproductions of Goethe's work after its original publication would have exposed him to Goethe's writing.

Under California law, could a customer who slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store sue for punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice about the spill and didn't clean it for half an hour as he was eating dinner? A judge would likely not dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim out of hand. To justify punitive damages, she must show the manager's actions were willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, and his conduct was despicable. The manager should have known the risk of not cleaning the spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured in similar incidents before Palmer's accident. While his actions were still despicable, they were not unreasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and the manager still failed to improve store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee at D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin replied that he was on dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, notified Martin about the spill, and he responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before her accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages, and we're considering whether to file a motion for partial summary against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct and willfully failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).
