The teachings of Jesus, as well as the beliefs he held in his lifetime, were quickly set aside as Christian thought moved forward after his life. Looking at history in broad terms, we see Christianity progressively drifting farther from its roots. Today, the world exhibits a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditionalists resist any new ideas, they may not have a significant influence on the whole. Among Christians, a historical consciousness will grow, leading to a desire to distinguish the doctrines added over time from the original intent of Christianity's namesake. This transformation may take decades or even centuries, but it's inevitable: a great reversal in Christian history is coming. There will be a return to Christianity's original form, with a movement growing to remove added doctrine layer by layer, as if the clock is turning back. This trend will sweep through the United States and Europe, leading to a worship experience similar to the time of Jesus, adhering to his ideas alone. The church will remain strong to guide this process, but it will also see a reversal in the proliferation of Christian diversity. Instead of differences, there will be increasing uniformity of belief and practice. History is filled with great reversals, such as the Roman Empire's transformation from persecutor to Christian institution. Our country has shifted from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The future reversion in Christianity will play out in the arena of faith, undoing history to find the source and reducing diversity in the process. This transformation will be possible through a metaphorical interpretation of Jesus' words, not as literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? Looking back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation of Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at Christianity's core by the time the Romans assumed control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united; they divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority were common people.

The Jungle exposes the intrinsic greed and self-interest of human nature. People inherently prioritize their own well-being and prosperity, rarely considering others less fortunate. The novel illustrates this through the factory owners and managers who are solely focused on expanding their business empires, disregarding anyone or anything that hinders their progress. Upton Sinclair portrays the destructive impact of their endeavors with vivid imagery, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." The owners care little for the detrimental effects on people and animals, as seen in the polluted skies and toxic waste from the thousands of pens around Packingtown. Their employees are also exploited, forced to labor long hours for little compensation and no job security. In the absence of protective regulations, managers and owners wielded power without restraint, driving workers to unsafe conditions and laboring until exhaustion. The workers were essentially treated as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers employ varied techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers. Some methods are more impactful than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs these techniques extensively in his novel The Great Gatsby. He frequently pairs words in unexpected ways to create a certain atmosphere around subjects. Additionally, he imbues symbols with meaning and then utilizes them for the same purpose. Fitzgerald does this with several colors, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald develops a significance for white/gray and later employs these colors to remind readers of certain feelings associated with important objects.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher-class, nicer standard, and gray signifying age and weariness. He establishes this meaning early in the novel with frequent uses of both colors. Throughout the book, characters are often seen in white, with Daisy and Jordan consistently “in white” (8), even Nick wears “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party, Tom has a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). The only time characters aren’t in white is when Nick offers his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald reinforces this color association by using white and gray to depict common, unimportant subjects: Nick’s commute to work is “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), Gatsby’s party guests have “gray names” (61), Catherine’s apartment is one slice in a long “white cake of apartment-houses” (28), and Jordan and Daisy share a “white girlhood” (19). He also describes plain or mundane people and places in white or gray: the “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “gray” Italian child on the train (26), and the dog-seller is a “gray old man” (27).

Once Fitzgerald has established enough meaning around white/gray, he uses these colors to signify uniformity or unimportance of certain subjects, starting with Daisy. After a period without any notable use of these colors, Daisy is described as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster,” making her appear less like a character and more like an object of desire for Gatsby (74). Fitzgerald continues this technique with Daisy, using a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her wearing a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter, further emphasizing her uniformity.

**San Diego County is a hotbed for farming, thanks to its pleasant, sunny climate. It's famous for crops like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a strong demand for organic, community-supported agriculture here, with many local orgs having long waiting lists for organic eggs and milk. Some organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This setup lets landowners enjoy government benefits, improve habitat, and create additional income streams or educational opportunities.**

**Organic farming brings more biodiversity to plants and wildlife, but it also comes with higher costs. It requires more labor and management to control pests, weeds, and fertilize the soil without chemicals. Unfortunately, losses are often higher than with conventional methods. Plus, small organic farms lack the scale efficiency of larger operations. Additional benefits for wildlife, like planting cover crops or managing plant growth, also come with higher labor costs. Thus, a landowner in this area might seek help or expertise to maximize profits and habitat quality.**

**The chosen parcel is next to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland near the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, part of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This plan includes over a hundred species, many of which are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. Others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.**

**This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later used by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. It was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and/or wood production for decades. The owner chose this piece of property and researched government programs to help a small farmer manage costs and preserve wildlife-friendly operations.**

Culture is mightily significant in any negotiation. It can be seen as much by what it is not as what it is, and what it represents. Culture isn't homogeneous or a specific thing. It's not singular or uniform. Sayings like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are broad and simplistic. While understanding the cultural norms is useful, it's more beneficial for a negotiator to grasp how culture's attitudes will impact the talks. When encountering a foreign culture, one experiences it through their own cultural lens, leading to inevitable comparisons.

Delving into a foreign culture or mindset could involve studying its history or acknowledging its biases. Instead of judging or trying to change it, one must simply accept it for what it is and work within its constraints, particularly when negotiating, especially if one has a weaker position at the table. If a negotiator finds themselves "away" in someone else's territory, respecting traditions and beliefs helps overcome cultural hurdles and move the negotiation forward.

Remember, culture isn't just about national or international differences. Many companies within a nation have their own unique corporate culture. For example, one might emphasize long hours while another promotes a more relaxed schedule. Signs of a company's culture can be seen in dress codes, communication styles (direct vs. indirect), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy at any level, while others restrict it to "company-approved" causes. Even within America, corporate cultures can vary greatly, from company to company and region to region, showing the diversity that can exist within a single societal culture. Some cultures might seem less stratified and more uniform, but an outsider should dig deeper to truly understand them.

Understanding values is crucial as they provide the "why" behind a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is valued, a negotiator won't publicly embarrass their company or superior. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture that values a hard-driven bargain won't rush to settle. Keeping these generalities in mind before the negotiation is essential. However, learning about one's opponent on a personal level can greatly enhance the negotiation's effectiveness.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This phrase appears initially in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is the opening line of St. Anselm’s argument regarding God's existence. Both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas share this belief and are defending the same concept, so we'll assume they are both correct for the sake of this discussion. Our task is to determine whose argument is stronger. To compare their arguments effectively, we must consider them as defenses of a specific God, as defined in the Bible. Neither truly offers a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

Let's start with St. Anselm's basic argument. He posits that understanding God comes from within oneself, through faith. He argues that God exists within our understanding, and we cannot comprehend his nonexistence. His proof lies in our inherent knowledge within our minds. This is a form of faith, as it requires acceptance of something not proven empirically.

Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, argues that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without the need for faith. This approach is advantageous for evangelism, as it allows for persuasion through logic. Aquinas presents five logical arguments supporting God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that God's existence is logically necessary. For instance, if you know you're missing one piece of a puzzle, you can infer its existence and features without seeing it.

Not too long ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future sage named Buddha was born. His life's journey led to enlightenment, and his teachings gave birth to Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional branch. Now, Buddhism is around 2,500 years old, and quite a few changes have occurred since Buddha's time. For example, in Sri Lanka, the Theravada nation, an annual water-cutting ceremony is observed, a ritual that Buddha never taught. This ceremony and many other practices differentiate the religion's surface and core beliefs. The Theravada Buddhist community has evolved over time, influenced by both internal and external factors, both hostile and benign.

In this discussion, several terms will be used often. Internal forces are those generated by Buddhists, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, born from negative perceptions of Buddhism. Benign forces, on the other hand, do not wish to harm or assist the community but may do so unintentionally.

Let's start with the basic doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma, composed of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—includes the Sutta Pitaka (Buddhist texts), the Vinaya Pitaka (disciplinary rules), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical aspects). Key metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these helps one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. When one becomes enlightened, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) also cease. The Vinaya Pitaka sets out rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts (not killing, not lying, not stealing, no misbehavior, and no intoxicants), while monks have many more rules to follow. The Four Noble Truths form the foundation of Buddhism: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a path to achieve this cessation.

The United States of America and Mexico once had a lengthy rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. attacked and conquered Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest. There were numerous skirmishes between the two nations, which finally eased just before the First World War. The rivalry began due to conflicts over religion, culture, tradition, and material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31). It's not unique to these two nations; bordering countries often have rivalries due to shared interests. David M. Pletcher (1977) observed, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find enduring American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). These nations are geographically close to the U.S. and have been rivals, unlike other Latin American nations that have maintained good relations with the U.S. Religious differences also played a significant role in the rivalry, stemming from historical distrust between the English and Spanish. This mistrust was a substantial barrier to friendly relations between the U.S. and Mexico. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes during this 57-year period, with most being territorial issues like border raids and frontier problems (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). The rivalry began to wane when Mexico became dependent on the U.S., and it finally ended as American interests shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention (Schmitt 1974 p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly struck down by an illness I had never even heard of. At the time, I was a dedicated nurse, having chosen this profession out of a deep-seated need for security and stability that eluded me in my youth. The promise of a job in nursing, regardless of my dreams of becoming a scientist or journalist, was a comforting mantra that echoed in my mind. Yet, here I was: 46 years old, alone, penniless, and unable to work. Despite 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I find myself with nothing left to call my own. Each day is a struggle, an onslaught on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is guaranteed anymore, but one thing is clear: I would not have survived these years without the support of my family and a few steadfast friends.

My point is that life is full of emergencies, whether big or small. No guarantees exist, and despite the best planning, some challenges are too great to face alone. While I agree that we should not rely solely on big government, I believe that Americans should once again learn to trust and help one another, rather than each of us individually preparing for disaster on our own.

Conservatives often tout the rugged individualism that supposedly built this nation, but in truth, it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources that kept our forefathers going. Pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains did not succeed by going it alone; they relied on each other.

So, by all means, prepare. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape for windows, flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm, learn to preserve your own food. It's a fantastic idea, but don't forget to get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change the way they do? Are there any limits or rules that guide the path of evolutionary change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson noted that even today, “the zoologist has only just begun to dream of defining organic forms in mathematical terms.” Yet, we are now applying mathematical modeling to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny, as illustrated by studies like Raup and Stanley's work in 1981. Our project aims to explore how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental research, can help us understand the mechanisms driving the pace and scale of evolutionary development. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to identify quantitative traits that can be used to model both theoretical and actual skeletal morphologies in the software program CerioShell. By doing this, we can interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum and combine these results with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this group.

Imagine a shell as a tube that unwinds through 360 degrees of space over time. These segments or coils are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The speed at which whorls grow can vary, and the continuous line separating each whorl is known as a suture. The largest whorl, which is the final one, is called the body whorl. The spire consists of all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is the base. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The common orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

Here's a method for counting whorls: First, view the shell from the apical side and locate the starting point of the first suture. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal grows its shell. By tracing the path of the aperture using the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture and the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture, we can create a graphical and mathematical representation. Once a mathematical formulation is established, we can adjust parameters to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has barely budged over the past decade. While the nation is on pace to meet several Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health is a significant letdown, failing to reach the desired targets by 2015. The myriad reasons behind this stagnation point to the need to fortify the overall health system, rather than relying on specific program interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled health workers, now at 72%, yet this includes traditional helpers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions in case of complications, leading to a high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. This improvement is somewhat misleading, indicating a lot more work to be done. Moreover, there's been a decline in children under five receiving treatment for diarrhea, and the data on postnatal care is incomplete, revealing widespread low rates across the country.

Cesarean-section rates remain low at 4%, with 7% in urban areas and only 2% in rural ones. This highlights the issue of inequitable access to healthcare, focusing mostly on urban areas. Another concern is vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor struggle more to access healthcare services due to high out-of-pocket costs.

When considering steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the critical question is how best to tackle the lack of service. Should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or bolster the entire health system without solely targeting pre and post-pregnancy care? Programmatic approaches seem appealing as they offer focused, manageable objectives and faster results. However, they also come with drawbacks. Heavy investment in one area can lead to funding shortages for others and may cause human resources to migrate to better-resourced sectors. Additionally, running multiple parallel programs can result in service duplication and increased paperwork.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous attention to detail and emphasis on the aristocracy of the era. Two notable novels that diverge from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both stories incorporate an element of mystery and the peculiar, which is uncommon for Victorian literature, thereby enriching the characters and offering insights into their motivations and emotions.

"Suddenly, a swarm of perplexing and disorienting ideas flooded his mind. He seemed to be walking again between Sikes and Crackit, engaged in a heated argument, for their voices echoed in his ears. When he snapped back to reality, he discovered he had been conversing with them. Abruptly, he flinched at the sound of gunfire; cries and shouts filled the air, and lights danced before his eyes. All was chaos and commotion, as an unseen force rushed him away. Throughout these rapid visions, an undefined, unsettling awareness of pain gnawed at him, tormenting him unceasingly."
(Dickens, 220)

The two novels often employ mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with the content and purpose varying in each instance. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences frequently reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, the pain that afflicts him, and his understanding of the true nature of his surroundings. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he relives the event vividly, as if in a dream, while desperately seeking help. The passage underscores Oliver's lack of control over the events unfolding, the precarious state of his health, and the constant pain that haunts him. The pain is now linked to fear rather than surprise, and he experiences his despair again, removed from the initial shock. The question arises of whose will brought about his misfortune, as it certainly wasn't his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, even his own fate. His inability to take action, even in the face of mortal danger, suggests a growing sense of defeat, as if Fagin had broken him, instilling this despair and influencing his ability to react. It can be assumed that otherwise, Oliver would have at least attempted to save himself.

A few years back, I tutored elementary school students in an after-school program. My expertise was in English and reading, and I did my best to assist them in these areas. However, my attention was drawn to a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade and had significant trouble reading, but his issues were peculiar. He could pronounce some letters perfectly, while others were off the mark, which was quite unusual. Adrian was of Latino descent, but he spoke English flawlessly. His mother spoke only Spanish, and our communication was aided by my limited Spanish knowledge, which I was just beginning to learn. It was then that it hit me: Adrian could read, but he struggled with the English alphabet. I'm not sure if this revelation helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. It proves that problems aren't always as apparent as we think. A child who speaks English fluently can still struggle with reading. This is a well-known problem, and solving it is complex. For Adrian, the solution was straightforward: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for children who barely speak English, the solution is much more intricate. There is no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will fix this problem. The key is combining all these elements.

Firstly, the dual language system is a fantastic idea, not just for Spanish-speaking children but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically." Many fear this system is a waste of resources and benefits only a minority of students. However, if implemented as the norm rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we achieve this? Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's unrealistic. Instead, we can have special helpers, tutors, or whatever you'd call them, who are bilingual.

From the time we're kids, we're told there's something out there, bigger than us, beyond our understanding. Some go to church, others to temples, or delve within for answers. Many accept what's been passed down by parents, but some reject it outright, dismissing it as just a part of their personal, limited universe. We choose our paths, searching for light to guide us out of the shadows. "A cardinal," my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, rain pounding on the tin roof, and I felt alone and afraid. I couldn't talk about missing him, so I just hugged him and sat close, watching the rain. My father passed in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had kept him alive, but he suffered longer than expected. I didn't want to watch him die, so I hid in my bed for days, waiting for news. No one called. I thought God had stopped listening, if he existed at all. I chose to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. I didn't want to be a spectator at his death. I just curled up and waited.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is often referred to as an "old-new oxymoron" by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. It has been both criticized and lauded for its "terrible sublime" aspect (Burke). The first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, cleverly blended ancient and modern romances to birth the proto-Gothic genre and a fresh literary approach. Walpole mixed old theatrical elements with new nature mimicry in his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). Gothic fiction often draws on medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, "gothic" was used to describe various cultures, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to modern society. The fusion of theatrical Gothic and the new novel format, offering a reader's personal view of character psychology, allowed Gothic to persist and evolve, remaining both obsolete and fresh for distant readers.

One key Gothic idea is chivalry. The medieval concept of training a proper knight is both preserved and transformed in Walpole's The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry was significant to Gothic writers as a symbol of the classic knight's bravery, honor, and competence, and as a perceived lack of these qualities in contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romanticism. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous time and facing unfair accusations, might have felt that the morality and innate goodness of people in the gothic era had been lost in present society. This is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits even before his introduction. He is a prince, affected by tragedy, and supposedly killed by infidels, embodying the trope of the gallant and courteous Knight, albeit exaggerated, foreshadowing the excess associated with Gothic storytelling (66).

Supply chain management is the flow of processes that transport goods from the moment a customer places an order through to the raw materials stage, production, distribution, and finally reaching the customer. The term "supply chain management" was coined by Keith Oliver, a consultant, in 1982. He described it as the overall process of planning, executing, and controlling activities in the supply chain to swiftly and efficiently meet the demands of customers. There are six key components to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these components to deliver the best possible customer service.

Hitler is still alive in Burma, according to a sign. Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, holding a cardboard sign with the chilling message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is an oppressive Southeast Asian country ruled over by a ruthless military regime that seized power through a coup d’état back in 1962. In 2007, a series of street protests erupted, led by scores of Burmese monks, earning the name "The Saffron Revolution." At first, the government tolerated the peaceful gatherings, but as the protests gained momentum, the military became increasingly violent, attacking monasteries and rounding up foreign journalists. One photographer, Kenji Nagai, was killed on September 27th, 2007, for simply being at a protest. The official death toll is 13, but a defecting colonel claims thousands more have been killed. This is not an isolated occurrence. Throughout history, numerous governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain total control over their citizens. From Roman emperors claiming divine right to rule to Japanese emperors believed to be gods leading their people to prosperity through Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president's weekly meetings with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, these tactics have been prevalent. Notable examples include the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to challenge the government's authoritarian rule, witnessing a wide range of death tolls, from 200 to 3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s saw Hutu militia groups, backed by the government, systematically killing Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of their ethnicity. Hitler's Third Reich also stands out as a grim example, where Jews and others of Jewish descent were systematically rounded up and killed over several years and countries.

Duke Ellington left a lasting impact on jazz, predominantly due to his enduring presence and his ability to guide his orchestra artistically. Often, Ellington’s piano playing was understated in his compositions, yet his genius lay in crafting complex, rich pieces that highlighted each band member’s unique skills. He structured his orchestra to allow soloists to improvise freely while also writing tightly arranged pieces and phrases that accentuated each musician’s style. This approach not only highlighted individual players but also created a harmonious tone that was specific to each piece. Ellington’s exceptional understanding of each player’s sound and their collective harmony enabled him to produce some of jazz’s most innovative and brilliant works.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s sound and innovation, noting his use of voice as a “jazz instrument” throughout his career. This is evident in his early piece “Creole Love Call,” where he employs voice to add texture and color without the distraction of lyrics. This slow, twelve-bar blues piece, with six choruses, demonstrates his ability to complement his soloists’ styles. Chorus 1 features a call and response between voice and reeds, transitioning from smooth to rough sounds; Chorus 2 has a muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the melody with extended blue notes; Chorus 3 showcases a sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase. Chorus 4 echoes the first with brass and reed call and responses; Chorus 5, the climactic chorus, sees reeds starting the call and response at a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from brass and rhythm sections. Chorus 6 returns to the structure of the first chorus, with the voice employing the “growl” technique for soloing. The piece ends with a vocal run and a dissonant trombone novelty. This use of voice adds a layer of tone color, a style that permeates much of Ellington’s work.

In “Hot and Bothered,” recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley’s muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing creates a rich, complementary sound by merging the vocal elements of Miley’s playing with the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice. “It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)” extends these ideas by using Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton’s muted trombone to great effect in introducing the melody.

She'd always felt like there was something missing, a yearning that couldn't be quenched. It began when she was 14, entering teenage life, and it was still there at 17. Initially, she desired an object, but her interests shifted to people, specifically boys. Yet, none captured her attention. She pondered why this was the case, but her reflections revealed no solid answers. So, she carried on with her life, puzzling over her desires.

Usually, her days at home were peaceful. Her parents were calm and rarely argued, except when she asserted her independence. They were a balanced pair, and she fit right in with her lively persona. But today was different. As she wandered her house in search of inspiration, she heard her mother's cry from the kitchen. Running in, she panicked and asked, "Mom?! What's wrong?!" Seeing her mother in pain, she rushed to her side. "Mom, let me help you," she said, attempting to assist. Her mother, in agony, directed her to take her to the hospital. Her daughter carried her mother to the car and drove off. The hospital was filled with the scent of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was focused on helping her mother. She carried her in quickly and called for help. A team of doctors rushed to her mother's aid. Her mother had fallen off a stool while trying to reach a high cabinet.

This investigation aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean" (aMed) diet score, is linked to a reduced likelihood of developing chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, and a lower risk of stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant foods (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), fish, and lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. It also permits moderate alcohol consumption.

Previous studies have shown an inverse relationship between following the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and a trial found the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet for promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. These studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, all participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. The researchers computed aMed diet scores six times between 1984 and 2004 from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of nurses remained in the study throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were verified through validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for each individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could skew results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

The study found that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. During the 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States was hit by a severe financial meltdown. Unemployment surged, the housing market collapsed, and many of the country's major corporations were left in ruins. This recession has lingered to this day, so we must ponder: what caused this crisis, and how can we prevent it in the future? Essentially, the financial crisis was sparked by self-serving and naive political decisions that coerced banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans, straining an already fragile and insufficient financial infrastructure. Simultaneously, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repackage these mortgages into CDO's and CDS', exacerbating the situation when borrowers defaulted on their loans. Banks, lacking sufficient capital reserves, passed on this chaos to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and ultimately, to the rest of the economy.

The financial crisis's roots date back to 1999, during the Clinton administration's push for a second term. To boost his popularity and secure reelection, the Clinton administration loosened lending restrictions, paving the way for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times, in 1999, warned, “Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, faced growing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand home loans for low- and moderate-income buyers, while stockholders pressured for continued profit growth.” Holmes foresaw the implications of these actions: “However, a government-subsidized corporation like Fannie Mae might face trouble in an economic downturn, necessitating a government rescue similar to the savings and loan industry's bailout in the 1980s.”

Multiple factors contributed to the economic downturn, including the complex new mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO's) became commonplace, further intertwining the economy with the housing market. This overexposure to housing market fluctuations left U.S. households and financial markets exceptionally vulnerable.

When the housing bubble burst, financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities were in distress. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, equal to about 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks under stringent regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That section in your story where you strut your stuff and wow everyone with your captivating, almost mystical writing style. Or that part where your readers nod off and hit the "Back" button, cursing your name. Dr. Merlin's been known to shriek at her screen when she stumbles into an info dump, and not in a fun way.

Exposition is your enemy.

Our dear readers already know the writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin can't help but find herself in long, boring passages. Exposition is the devil on your shoulder urging you to quickly get the history out of the way to get to the good parts, not to be confused with the other shoulder devil demanding to tell the audience every detail of everyone's childhood.

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, often in simple prose. In movies, exposition occurs when one character dumps information on another, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author's doing the talking.

Let's look at an example. You're reading a story, and you're told the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, got married in a grand ceremony, and her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this to take two pages with mere lines of dialogue. You'd expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his speech and actions how much he loves his wife, and the heroine to show how his presence enriched her life. A proper introduction would make you care about his fate and give you insight into the heroine's character: her thoughts, dreams, and beliefs as seen through his eyes. You'd grieve with her and grow more connected to her.

In short, you'd expect substance to the story's basic plot: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*Looks at metaphor, sighs, presses on*) Sometimes, it's tempting to rush past certain things. Maybe you're introducing a new character and you know he was in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, was married twice, has no kids, likes fishing, dreams of owning the station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I tuned into two broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio today. The first was a live stream on NBC 4. The top story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his was Shad Hostettler. They displayed his mugshot, and he looked menacing. They allocated about two minutes to this developing story, which I thought was fitting. The second news story was about an early morning shooting in the Sharon Woods area that left Travis Buyers, 18, critically injured. There were no arrests yet, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story was rather brief, and I believe that might be due to the fact that the victim was a minority. I've noticed this pattern over the years: when a white child or adult is a crime victim, the media goes into frenzy, but if it's a minority, it's lucky if it's even covered. The third story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, with details about the incident. The bullet was determined to be a .22 caliber from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers is offering a five-thousand-dollar reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest. Next, they ran a story about predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon, with weekend temperatures expected to be mid to low eighties. This story was a bit short, but it was used as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in. Another story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, where a dark-skinned black man in a hoodie sweatshirt robbed the store. They devoted an unusual amount of time discussing his race and exactly how dark his skin was. The final story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin, who was sentenced to over 25 years for conspiring to distribute marijuana to Ohio from Texas. Oddly, they mentioned that his sentence was 300 months instead of 25 years, and they also noted his Hispanic ethnicity, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

The relationship between brothers is a unique one, with an unbreakable bond that encompasses numerous emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. They understand each other better than anyone else and see themselves in their brothers. It is in times of dire need that this bond reveals its true nature, for better or for worse. When these emotions become apparent, they come with a price. Understanding the emotions that stem from this fraternal bond also means accepting the consequences they bring. When one looks into their brother's eyes, they see not just the other person, but a reflection of themselves, their true self. Their actions and the repercussions of those actions expose their genuine character. In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers delve into this theme and the complex emotions it entails. Through a lush, vibrant landscape, they embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment and intense pride climax in the final scene, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as the narrator’s perspective on the protagonist’s feelings and his view of the world, both of which heavily influence his actions.

The protagonist’s actions are largely driven by one key emotion: pride. From their initial outings to their final, fateful adventure, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He wanted a brother he could teach his various skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” and someone to race to Horsehead Landing with and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn… These were dreams he had for his brother, but Doodle’s frail health made it unlikely he would even survive, let alone participate in such activities. The contrast between his lofty plans and the harsh reality was a blow to the young protagonist. To his credit, he bears some anger towards the small child, contemplating suffocating him with a pillow when the boy smiled at him. This shows his conviction was not too strong. The simple act of Doodle smiling at him softened his heart, demonstrating an inherent love for his brother, perhaps stronger than he initially thought.

The human brain is a complex, innovative data-processing system. As tech advanced, the metaphors used to describe it evolved too. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a scroll, then to a book, and now to a computer. As you learn about the brain, remember that these metaphors are helpful but can also lead to mistakes.

Information processing begins with the senses, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. The brain reworks this information through algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple info like color and borders to identify the box. Top-down processing speeds up recognition by considering previous decisions. For example, it might help you identify it as a black box rather than a hole.

Once processed, an attention filter decides what's crucial and which cognitive processes should access it. For instance, while your brain processes every blade of grass when looking at your shoes, a healthy attention filter ignores them. However, you might notice your name in a noisy room. There are many processing stages, and attention modulates the results repeatedly.

To process info, the brain first stores it. There are sensory, working, and long-term memories. Information is encoded based on the type of stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded by its structure, sound, or meaning. Once stored, it must be maintained. Some studies suggest that working memory, which holds info for about 20 seconds, is maintained by a loop of electrical signals in neurons.

There are various models for how knowledge is organized in the brain. Some are based on how humans recall memories, others on computer science, and more on neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that there are nodes representing concepts, linked by their relatedness. For example, in this model, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so on.

In Aldous Huxley's Brave New World, the looming threat of technology and capitalism is starkly depicted through a dystopian society where individuals are conditioned to prioritize immediate happiness and collective harmony over individuality. The citizens are pawns in an elaborate system controlled by the World Controller, who manipulates them through hypnopædia and ideological conditioning. The novel, when examined through a Marxist lens, reveals Huxley's critique of the economic and social structures of his time. Terms like homogenization and reification emphasize the loss of individual identity and autonomy in this society.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness. The common people are kept unaware of their true economic relations, consumed by personal gain and the drive to consume. The World Controller ensures that the lower classes, Deltas and Gammas, remain in their places through hypnopædia, fostering a culture of consumption. Hegemony is evident in the societal structure, where the upper classes benefit from the subjugation of the lower classes. The interactions between social classes highlight the oppressive nature of capitalism. Love and deep emotions are absent, with relationships reduced to mere physical appearances and superficial encounters. Each class maintains their status through compliance, reflecting Marxist ideas about the proletariat's false sense of superiority and their dependence on consumption.

I've been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years, or roughly four and a half semesters. Navigating campus can be quite the challenge, and I'm not the only one who feels this way. My freshman year, I was placed in an East Halls dorm room, which is basically the farthest spot from the center of campus. Getting to classes in places like the Willard building from there could take up to 25 minutes, especially in our infamous State College weather. I spoke with an alum who told me that not too long ago, the East Halls were separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Now, that space has been filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and surrounding apartment complexes. As our campus keeps expanding, it's becoming increasingly difficult to get from one place to another. So, what's the best solution for campus mobility? For many students, the answer is the bicycle. But a bike alone isn't enough. Students need to be encouraged to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed with bicycle-friendly routes in mind.

I had a chat with a friend who recently picked up biking again after a few years. He mentioned how he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are amazing," he said, "for a while, they weren't cool, but they're the only practical way to get around." Biking is not only good for your health but also the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exertion can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergrads, I've moved off campus, roughly the same distance from the center as some of the dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was buying a bike. I have classes in the Thomas building, which would take me about 25 minutes to walk to, but only 5 minutes on a bike if I pedal fast. The only downside is that Pollock Road, the direct path to Thomas, can be quite challenging. While walking has its benefits, I simply don't have the time. Without a bike, walking would be my only reliable option. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, and that's over two and a half hours a week. And that's not counting the time I'd need for other classes, appointments, and so on. That's more time than I can spare.
